06458nam a22008295i 9786155211591DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222008hu     fo  d z      eng d  a97861552115917 a10.1515/97861552115912doi  a(DE-B1597)633327  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 4aBD638b.G25 2008eb 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a11522200aGiven World and Time :bTemporalities in Context /ced. by Tyrus Miller. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (375 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tTemporality in the Long Run -- t1. Walking Backwards into the Future: The Conception of Time in the Ancient Near East -- t2. Epic Remains: Seeing and Time in the Odyssey -- t3. Fourier and the Saint-Simonians on the Shape of History -- t4. World History According to Katrina -- tHistorical Figures: Mediations, Citations, Narrations -- t5. Intricate Temporalities: The Transfiguration of Proper and “Improper” Sounds from Christian to Jewish Environments -- t6. Quoting from the Past or Dealing with Temporality -- t7. Taking Time: Temporal Representations and Cultural Politics -- t8. Image-Times, Image-Histories, Image-Thinking -- t9. Documentary Re-enactments: A Paradoxical Temporality That Is Not One -- tShapes of Modernity -- t10. Time and Progress—Time as Progress: An Enlightened Sermon by William Robertson -- t11. Religious Revivals: The Binds of Religion and Modernity in Friedrich Nietzsche’s The Anti-Christ and Richard Wright’s The Outsider -- t12. Hetero-Temporalities of Post-Socialism -- t13. The Politics of Temporality: Heidegger, Bourdieu, Benjamin, Derrida -- t“To the Planetarium”: From Cosmos to History and Back -- t14. Eternity No More: Walter Benjamin on the Eternal Return -- t15. A Microscope for Time: What Benjamin and Klages, Einstein and the Movies Owe to Distant Stars -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe interconnections of time with historical thought and knowledge have come powerfully to the fore since the 1970s. An international group of scholars, from a range of fields including literary theory, history of ideas, cultural anthropology, philosophy, intellectual history and theology, philology, and musicology, address the matter of time and temporalities.The volume's essays, divided into four main topical groups question critically the key problem of context, connecting it to the problem of time. Contexts, the essays suggest, are not timeless. Time and its contexts are only partly "given" to us: to the primordial donations of time and world correspond our epistemic, moral, and practical modes of receiving what has been granted. The notion of context may have radically different parameters in different historical, cultural, and disciplinary situations. Topics include the deep antiquity, and the timeless time of eternity, as well as formal philosophies of history and the forms of histories implicit in individual and community experience. The medium specific use of time and history are examined with regard to song, image, film, oral narration, and legal discourse.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aTime. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aEnlightenment, Historiography, Modernity, Philosophy, Political philosophy, Post-communism, Time.1 aBassi, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeecher, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClausberg, Karl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCouzens Hoy, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator